LPJ-Guess

This project is being worked on in collaboration with Charlotte Uden and Greta Savitsky. My primary role has been analyzing data provided by Charlotte to assist in her Ph.d thesis, specifically regarding outputs in the LPJ-Guess Dynamic Vegetation-Terrestrial Ecosystem Model. Charlotte seeks to use forest composition predicted by LPJ-Guess to understand the role of fire on the pre-European landscape of the Northeastern United States. The goal is to correctly model current environmental and testable metrics within LPJ_Guess, in an effort to extrapolate the parameters into the past, to enable predictive (Is it post-dictive when predicting the past?) analysis.

Data Overview

The data provided for this analysis was 10 sets of 142,681 observations with 12 categories, totaling in 17,121,720 data points.
The 10 sets were made up of different fire frequencies, ranging from 1 (Most) to 0 (Least). The categories were filled with the following six plant functional types (PFTs):

  • BNT: Boreal Needleleaf Shade Tolerant
  • BNI: Boreal Needleleaf Shade Intolerant
  • TBT: Temperate Broadleaved Shade Tolerant
  • BBI: Boreal Broadleaved Shade Intolerant
  • TBI: Temperate Broadleaved Shade Intolerant
  • TBIR: Temperate Broadleaved Shade Intolerant - Fire Resilient

Additionally, location data (Lat, Long), Year, and Total density for location was provided.

Analysis

I was tasked with investigating if tree density changes with fire frequency, as well as viewing historical density outputs from the model.

Since I was not looking at geographical data for this specific investigation, I generated alternative datasets containing only relevant data (Lat/Long removal) to ease in both organization and accelerate processing time.

The analysis produced (Figure 1, Figure 2, Figure 3) is Total Density by Year, separated by Fire Frequency. In this, I wanted to investigate what type of effect Fire Frequency was having on the entire forest density ecosystem. Three test graphs were produced to determine which would be the best for relaying this information visually; we found each offers a unique utilization. Trends appear to hold consistent regardless of Fire Frequency with regards to Year, but I have not yet run a statistical test to verify.

What Figure 3 was able to clearly show, was that there was a jump in Total Density at Fire Frequency 0.05 and 1. I found this interesting, and set out to examine the data more closely, to see there were any PFT differences happening within these macro jumps; specifically, was the distribution equally distributed across the board.

Figure 1: Total Tree Density Through Year - Overview

Figure 2: Total Tree Density Through Year - Sequential

Figure 3: Total Tree Density Through Year: Side by Side

Since Density was trending consistently through Year, I decided to run a separate analysis without Year as a consideration. Figure 4 is Plant Density by Fire Probability, separated by Plant Functional Type. What I found in this analysis was intriguing; while the Total Density markers reflect the output produced in the previous analysis (Rise in Total Plant Density on Fire Probability 0.05 and 1), the individual Plant Functional Types do not all align neatly. While BNT, BNI, and TBT rise on the Fire Probability 0.05 and 1 markers, BBI, TBI, and TBIR reverse.

When presented to the group, this was somewhat unexpected. However, we have thought about the results and determined that it may mean that the LPJ-Guess and Charlottes’ inputs are working correctly - on further analysis, we came to the conclusion that we should not expect all PFTs to function the same with regards to Density and Fire Frequency, as they have different traits, weaknesses, and strengths.

We are looking to investigate this further; I am currently awaiting additional data from Charlotte, specifically Tree Diameter - which we hope will further help us uncover the secrets of this virtual forest.

Figure 4: Plant Density by Fire Probability, Seperated by PFT

cleanup <- function(data=x, fireprob=y) { 
  #rename columns
  names(data) <- c("Lon","Lat","year","BNT","BNI","TBT","BBI","TBI","TBIR", "C3G", "C4G","Total")
  #remove first row - for some reason output had headers as athe firs row
  data <- data[-c(1),] 
  data[,1] <- as.numeric(paste(data$Lon))
  data[,2] <- as.numeric(paste(data$Lat))
  data[,3] <- as.numeric(paste(data$year))
  data[,4] <- as.numeric(paste(data$BNT))
  data[,5] <- as.numeric(paste(data$BNI))
  data[,6] <- as.numeric(paste(data$TBT))
  data[,7] <- as.numeric(paste(data$BBI))
  data[,8] <- as.numeric(paste(data$TBI))
  data[,9] <- as.numeric(paste(data$TBIR))
  data[,10] <- as.numeric(paste(data$C3G))
  data[,11] <- as.numeric(paste(data$C4G))
  data[,12] <- as.numeric(paste(data$Total))
  
  #add a column with fire probability
  fireprob <- rep(fireprob, times=nrow(data))
  data <- cbind(data, fireprob)
  
  return(data)
}
